@carver what do you think about testing via something like this using middleware to simulate a transaction not yet being mined.

```
counter = itertools.counter()
def unmined_receipt_simulator_middleware(make_request, web3):
    receipt_counters = collections.defaultdict(itertools.counter)

    def middleware(method, params):
        if method == 'eth_getTransactionReceipt':
            txn_hash = params[0]
            if next(receipt_counters[txn_hash]) < 2:
                return {'result': None}
        return make_request(method, params)
    return middleware
```

@johnsca 

> I don't think it's at all true that a charm upgrade implies an application upgrade.

I think the issue I have is that a resource update triggers `upgrade-charm` hook and we currently don't have a different way to react to that. If we can really decouple the two (charm and application upgrade), then I think the name `upgrade.charm.completed` is good.

@migurski I like your idea of renaming these function to avoid confusion as well as the new names being more indicative of their function. I've implemented this change accordingly.

Yes these two operations would be identical. I believe that we should continue to have both as the space delimited option is the one used most often but in order to remain backwards compatible we just support the `separator` type as well. This will also be required to support hyphenated street numbers.

The regex used is PCRE style regex. Javascript regex is almost PCRE compliant but is flawed in that it lacks support when using look arounds. Based on the sources that will benefit from this function I think look-arounds are a integral.

